The Constitution of Norway was signed at Eidsvoll on May 17 in the year 1814. The constitution declared Norway to be an independent nation-state, in an attempt to avoid being ceded to Sweden after Denmark-Norway's devastating defeat in the Napoleonic Wars. Shortly after, a war was fought between Norway and Sweden. Norway lost the war, but instead of being ceded to Sweden, it entered a personal union with them, known as the United Kingdoms of Sweden and Norway (for short: Sweden-Norway). This union was dissolved in 1905.
